00:18:19,727 --> 00:18:22,094
[ ♫ Singing Indistinctly ♫ ]

278
00:18:36,076 --> 00:18:37,907
[ Grunts ]

279
00:18:37,978 --> 00:18:41,061
Jesus.
You bring me luck.

280
00:18:41,792 --> 00:18:43,316
- Luck?

281
00:18:43,417 --> 00:18:45,715
Haven't had much.

282
00:18:45,786 --> 00:18:47,156
- Everyone needs luck.

283
00:18:47,187 --> 00:18:50,757
They do.
Not everyone gets it.

284
00:18:50,788 --> 00:18:52,662
- Maybe it's your turn.

285
00:18:52,693 --> 00:18:53,926
That would be nice.

286
00:18:54,957 --> 00:18:59,102
Right, come over here.
Help me tie their claws.

287
00:18:59,633 --> 00:19:04,440
Right, put one in between your
legs so he doesn't bite you.

288
00:19:04,471 --> 00:19:07,273
And just do the other one like this.

289
00:19:09,075 --> 00:19:10,266
What do you do with them?

290
00:19:10,297 --> 00:19:11,611
- What do you think?

291
00:19:11,652 --> 00:19:12,968
Eat them.

292
00:19:13,199 --> 00:19:15,519
No. Sell them.

293
00:19:16,550 --> 00:19:18,250
You always catch this much?

294
00:19:18,281 --> 00:19:21,220
No. Almost never.

295
00:19:23,723 --> 00:19:25,061
Right.

296
00:19:25,492 --> 00:19:28,528
There you go.
Claws there.

297
00:19:28,559 --> 00:19:30,130
Grab that.

298
00:19:34,401 --> 00:19:36,906
It wasn't your song, you know.
Couldn't have been.

299
00:19:36,997 --> 00:19:38,137
- No.

300
00:19:38,189 --> 00:19:40,140
They were already in the pots.

300
00:19:40,308 --> 00:19:42,577
[ ♫ Music: Lisa Hannigan "Lille" ♫ ]

301
00:19:42,708 --> 00:19:44,577
♫ I went to war ♫

302
00:19:44,578 --> 00:19:47,279
♫ every morning ♫

303
00:19:47,280 --> 00:19:49,916
♫ I lost my way ♫

304
00:19:49,917 --> 00:19:53,185
♫ but now I'm following ♫

305
00:19:53,186 --> 00:19:58,825
♫ what you said in my arms ♫

306
00:19:58,826 --> 00:20:04,430
♫ what I read in the charms ♫

307
00:20:04,431 --> 00:20:08,367
♫ that I love durably ♫

308
00:20:08,368 --> 00:20:10,869
Why you put them back?

309
00:20:12,272 --> 00:20:14,440
Save them for a rainy day.

310
00:20:14,941 --> 00:20:16,642
We sell the rest.

311
00:20:20,246 --> 00:20:22,982
We'll get something for these.
- We?

312
00:20:22,983 --> 00:20:25,050
Your share of the catch.

313
00:20:26,587 --> 00:20:28,253
You did sing.

314
00:20:28,254 --> 00:20:30,322
Just don't go around town
singing for everyone.

315
00:20:30,493 --> 00:20:33,358
Come on into the co-op.
We'll get 10 euro a pound.

316
00:20:34,160 --> 00:20:36,529
I don't want to meet anyone.

317
00:20:37,964 --> 00:20:39,832
You've met me.

318
00:20:41,234 --> 00:20:43,168
You're the only one.

319
00:20:44,908 --> 00:20:46,105
Okay.

320
00:20:54,447 --> 00:20:55,447
How are you, Mary?

321
00:20:55,478 --> 00:20:57,109
- All right, Circus.

322
00:20:57,150 --> 00:20:58,850
- Oh, you done well today, then.

323
00:20:58,881 --> 00:21:01,056
Yes, for a change.

324
00:21:01,087 --> 00:21:02,668
And they say there's no lobster left.

325
00:21:02,699 --> 00:21:04,317
They do.

326
00:21:05,358 --> 00:21:07,025
Thank you very much.

327
00:21:07,126 --> 00:21:08,395
- Lovely.

328
00:21:20,940 --> 00:21:22,841
Can I help you, Circus?

329
00:21:22,942 --> 00:21:24,803
Tracy, would this go near you?

330
00:21:24,844 --> 00:21:26,559
You want me to try it?

331
00:21:26,590 --> 00:21:28,314
Okay.

332
00:21:37,156 --> 00:21:38,890
[ Curtain Closes ]

333
00:21:56,409 --> 00:21:59,037
It's a bit tight around here.

334
00:21:59,078 --> 00:22:01,813
At least you're not invisible.
- What?

335
00:22:01,914 --> 00:22:04,550
Nothing.
I'll take it.

336
00:22:04,551 --> 00:22:06,011
For who?

337
00:22:06,052 --> 00:22:08,003
Just for Annie.

338
00:22:08,054 --> 00:22:10,583
- This would never fit Annie.

339
00:22:10,624 --> 00:22:12,924
It will some day.

340
00:22:14,026 --> 00:22:15,901
What do you think, Circus?

341
00:22:15,962 --> 00:22:17,429
I think that's not my name.

342
00:22:17,490 --> 00:22:20,031
Sorry... Da.

343
00:22:21,100 --> 00:22:22,501
Do they give you a hard time?

344
00:22:22,552 --> 00:22:23,835
No, they're jealous.

345
00:22:23,886 --> 00:22:26,138
How many of them have
their own set of wheels?

346
00:22:26,159 --> 00:22:28,007
Motorized wheels!

347
00:22:31,678 --> 00:22:33,305
What are we doing?

348
00:22:33,346 --> 00:22:34,713
I was going to drive you home.

349
00:22:34,754 --> 00:22:36,214
I'll race you.

350
00:22:36,265 --> 00:22:39,077
Annie.
 - Yeah?

351
00:22:39,118 --> 00:22:41,253
Go on so.

352
00:22:47,694 --> 00:22:50,046
So, what's the story?

353
00:22:50,697 --> 00:22:52,665
Oh, she sings.

354
00:22:52,696 --> 00:22:54,199
Who sings?

355
00:22:54,240 --> 00:22:55,904
The woman in the story
I told you about.

356
00:22:55,935 --> 00:22:57,202
With the fisherman?

357
00:22:57,233 --> 00:22:58,260
Yes.

358
00:22:58,291 --> 00:23:01,307
She sings to the fishes,
and he catches them.

359
00:23:01,348 --> 00:23:03,108
You sure you're not dreaming, da?

360
00:23:03,139 --> 00:23:04,300
Dreaming?

361
00:23:04,331 --> 00:23:05,544
Yeah.
You sure this isn't

362
00:23:05,575 --> 00:23:07,660
some weird wish-fulfillment
kind of thing?

363
00:23:07,691 --> 00:23:09,247
Where did you learn words like that?

364
00:23:09,288 --> 00:23:11,263
I go to school.
- And I didn't? 

365
00:23:11,294 --> 00:23:13,822
No. Let's be honest, you didn't.

366
00:23:13,853 --> 00:23:15,454
You move your mouth when you read.

367
00:23:15,485 --> 00:23:16,759
Is that bad?

368
00:23:16,790 --> 00:23:20,115
No, but it means something.
So she sings, does she?

369
00:23:20,256 --> 00:23:23,329
Yeah. A song in a language
 he has never heard.

370
00:23:23,360 --> 00:23:25,431
That would be selk.
- Selk?

371
00:23:25,462 --> 00:23:28,293
A kind of seal talk.
And do you know why she sings?

372
00:23:28,324 --> 00:23:29,274
Why?

373
00:23:29,305 --> 00:23:30,959
That's the way
they communicate underwater.

374
00:23:30,990 --> 00:23:32,604
They don't speak, they sing.

375
00:23:32,645 --> 00:23:34,973
Ah. So the lobster hear her singing.

376
00:23:35,014 --> 00:23:36,407
What lobster?

377
00:23:36,508 --> 00:23:39,845
What I mean is, under the water
they hear her singing.

378
00:23:39,886 --> 00:23:42,504
The denizens of the deep.
- Are you sure?

379
00:23:42,545 --> 00:23:44,353
She's a seal.
She's not human.

380
00:23:44,384 --> 00:23:45,818
- She looks human.

381
00:23:45,859 --> 00:23:46,952
In the story?

382
00:23:46,993 --> 00:23:48,557
Yes, in the story.

383
00:23:48,598 --> 00:23:50,088
Whose story is this?

384
00:23:50,139 --> 00:23:52,123
It's mine.
- You're making it up?

385
00:23:52,154 --> 00:23:53,902
Yeah. For you.

386
00:23:53,993 --> 00:23:55,661
What are you planning for the weekend?

387
00:23:55,692 --> 00:23:57,731
Practicing my new wheels.

388
00:23:59,332 --> 00:24:01,132
Curious.

389
00:24:01,133 --> 00:24:03,869
♫ I went to sleep ♫

390
00:24:03,890 --> 00:24:06,705
♫ for the daytime ♫

391
00:24:06,736 --> 00:24:09,641
♫ shut my eyes ♫

392
00:24:09,672 --> 00:24:12,444
♫ to the sunshine ♫

393
00:24:12,475 --> 00:24:18,216
♫ turned my head away
from the noise ♫

394
00:24:18,247 --> 00:24:23,889
♫ bruise and drip decay
of childish toys ♫

395
00:24:23,920 --> 00:24:26,625
♫ that I loved ♫

396
00:24:26,656 --> 00:24:29,428
♫ arguably ♫

397
00:24:29,459 --> 00:24:35,000
♫ all our labouring
gone to seed ♫

398
00:24:40,840 --> 00:24:42,441
Got you some things.

399
00:24:42,482 --> 00:24:44,713
Things?
- Messages.

400
00:24:44,744 --> 00:24:46,157
Messages?

401
00:24:46,188 --> 00:24:48,039
Food and stuff.

402
00:24:48,080 --> 00:24:52,150
Even girls from the water
need to eat, right?

403
00:24:52,191 --> 00:24:54,486
Need clothes.

404
00:25:02,962 --> 00:25:04,994
Need to...

405
00:25:05,565 --> 00:25:08,700
tie their shoelaces.

406
00:25:24,248 --> 00:25:26,418
Curiouser and curiouser.

407
00:25:31,540 --> 00:25:32,924
You know my size?

408
00:25:33,065 --> 00:25:38,430
Tracy in the shop --
she looked like... your size.

409
00:25:43,535 --> 00:25:44,836
Thank you.

410
00:25:47,873 --> 00:25:49,545
Can I--?
- What?

411
00:25:49,596 --> 00:25:51,770
Can I clean up this place?

412
00:25:51,811 --> 00:25:53,411
I suppose.

413
00:25:53,462 --> 00:25:55,608
How long are you staying?

414
00:25:56,649 --> 00:25:59,745
Depends, I guess.
- On what?

415
00:25:59,786 --> 00:26:01,488
On you.

416
00:26:03,189 --> 00:26:04,336
On me?

417
00:26:04,377 --> 00:26:06,959
It depends on me,
you can stay forever.

418
00:26:06,990 --> 00:26:09,905
Forever?
- Forever.

419
00:26:09,996 --> 00:26:13,231
Happily ever after.
Once upon a time.

420
00:26:18,004 --> 00:26:21,840
I've been telling my daughter a story.

421
00:26:24,210 --> 00:26:26,612
A fairy tale.

422
00:26:43,730 --> 00:26:46,464
What's the story, da?

423
00:26:47,967 --> 00:26:50,101
Librarian: That's great.
See you, Deirdre.

424
00:26:56,843 --> 00:26:57,946
Hi, Annie.

425
00:26:57,977 --> 00:26:59,945
Gosh, you've a load of books there.

426
00:26:59,976 --> 00:27:01,413
I'm researching.

427
00:27:01,464 --> 00:27:04,052
Researching what?

428
00:27:04,083 --> 00:27:06,351
Something on seals, is it?

429
00:27:15,995 --> 00:27:18,730
My name's Syracuse,
and I'm an alcoholic.

430
00:27:18,761 --> 00:27:20,331
I've told you before, Circus,

431
00:27:20,362 --> 00:27:23,268
that confessional is not a chapter of AA.

432
00:27:23,299 --> 00:27:25,270
- There's none in this town, father.

433
00:27:36,716 --> 00:27:40,752
I've been sober 2 years,
7 months, and 18 days.

434
00:27:42,622 --> 00:27:45,460
This is where they all clap, father.

435
00:27:45,491 --> 00:27:46,959
Where did you see that,
in the movies?

436
00:27:46,990 --> 00:27:48,677
- Yes.

437
00:27:48,728 --> 00:27:50,462
Thank you.

438
00:27:50,493 --> 00:27:51,930
So, tell me.

439
00:27:51,961 --> 00:27:53,869
I had a dream, father.

440
00:27:53,900 --> 00:27:55,734
I'm at his funeral,
and she's beside me,

441
00:27:55,765 --> 00:27:58,369
And I'm panicking again.

442
00:27:58,399 --> 00:28:00,338
Maybe you still want to be with her.

443
00:28:00,369 --> 00:28:03,742
No. No, I'm panicking
because I'm back with her.

444
00:28:03,793 --> 00:28:07,005
Can't happen.
She's still drinking.

445
00:28:07,046 --> 00:28:08,246
All I want is Annie.

446
00:28:08,287 --> 00:28:11,009
Perhaps you need
to talk to someone, Circus.

447
00:28:11,050 --> 00:28:13,909
It's Syracuse.
And I'm talking to you.

448
00:28:13,940 --> 00:28:16,347
No, I mean a counselor.

449
00:28:16,388 --> 00:28:18,203
I could put you both
in touch with one

450
00:28:18,244 --> 00:28:20,158
if you'd give me permission.

451
00:28:20,189 --> 00:28:21,630
You have no permission.

452
00:28:21,661 --> 00:28:24,222
I only talk to you
because it's secret.

453
00:28:24,263 --> 00:28:26,458
Whenever you feel able to, tell me,

454
00:28:26,499 --> 00:28:29,304
and I'll set it in motion.

455
00:28:29,345 --> 00:28:34,305
Until then, try to control your feelings.

456
00:28:36,885 --> 00:28:38,707
Anything else?

457
00:28:39,778 --> 00:28:41,674
I suppose there is.

458
00:28:42,995 --> 00:28:45,177
Yeah, I stole.

459
00:28:45,918 --> 00:28:49,514
Oh, dear.
What did you steal, Syracuse?

460
00:28:49,555 --> 00:28:52,851
Some... Ladies' clothes.

461
00:28:52,892 --> 00:28:55,087
Oh, dear, dear, dear, dear.

462
00:28:55,128 --> 00:28:57,165
I don't like this at all, Syracuse.

463
00:28:57,196 --> 00:28:58,620
This is a bad development.

464
00:28:58,661 --> 00:29:00,231
Oh, it's not what you're thinking,
father.

465
00:29:00,262 --> 00:29:02,067
There was a reason.
- What was the reason?

466
00:29:02,098 --> 00:29:03,401
I stole them

467
00:29:03,432 --> 00:29:05,807
because I was embarrassed
to be seen buying them.

468
00:29:05,848 --> 00:29:07,039
What did you want them for?

469
00:29:07,080 --> 00:29:08,954
They were for this girl I met, father.

470
00:29:08,995 --> 00:29:12,943
A girl?
Where did you meet this girl?

471
00:29:14,714 --> 00:29:18,343
I pulled her out of the water
in my net.

472
00:29:18,384 --> 00:29:19,865
In your net?

473
00:29:19,896 --> 00:29:21,419
- In my fishing net.

474
00:29:21,460 --> 00:29:23,521
You're joking, surely, Syracuse?

475
00:29:23,662 --> 00:29:25,303
No, I'm not joking.

476
00:29:25,344 --> 00:29:26,662
Dreaming, maybe.

477
00:29:26,693 --> 00:29:29,061
But sure I went back to my boat
this morning, and...

478
00:29:29,092 --> 00:29:30,662
there she was.

479
00:29:30,693 --> 00:29:32,601
And did she
[ Clears Throat ]

480
00:29:32,631 --> 00:29:34,599
spend the night in the boat?

481
00:29:34,640 --> 00:29:36,101
[ Chuckles ]

482
00:29:36,132 --> 00:29:38,403
No.
- No?

483
00:29:38,434 --> 00:29:41,743
So, where did this girl sleep?

484
00:29:41,874 --> 00:29:44,006
I'm not telling you.

485
00:29:44,077 --> 00:29:46,644
- No. I can't force you to, can I?

486
00:29:46,675 --> 00:29:49,350
No.
And you can't tell anyone, either.

487
00:29:49,381 --> 00:29:52,150
No, my lips are sealed.

488
00:29:52,181 --> 00:29:56,321
But you'll keep me
informed of developments, Syracuse?

489
00:29:56,362 --> 00:29:57,804
Definitely, father.

490
00:29:59,135 --> 00:30:01,392
So, will I see you at mass on Sunday?

491
00:30:01,433 --> 00:30:03,165
You know you won't, father.

492
00:30:03,196 --> 00:30:05,767
I suppose I do.
You only avail of the confessional--

493
00:30:05,798 --> 00:30:08,459
Because there's no AA chapter
in this poxy town.

494
00:30:08,500 --> 00:30:10,839
I suppose you wouldn't say
a couple of 'hail Marys'

495
00:30:10,870 --> 00:30:12,170
on the way out, would you?

496
00:30:15,942 --> 00:30:18,676
[ ♫ Distant Rock Music Plays ♫ ]

497
00:30:37,563 --> 00:30:39,334
What are you reading, Annie?

498
00:30:39,365 --> 00:30:41,532
For school. Selkies.

499
00:30:41,533 --> 00:30:44,019
Selkies?
They're a Scottish thing.

500
00:30:44,070 --> 00:30:46,271
This one isn't.

501
00:30:52,145 --> 00:30:55,814
[ ♫ Humming ♫ ]

502
00:31:33,252 --> 00:31:35,520
[ ♫ Continues Humming ♫ ]

503
00:33:00,993 --> 00:33:03,642
Curiouser and curiouser.

504
00:33:06,212 --> 00:33:07,349
What's that?

505
00:33:07,380 --> 00:33:10,081
What Alice said to the white rabbit.

506
00:33:11,993 --> 00:33:13,451
Come again?

507
00:33:13,952 --> 00:33:16,487
- Curiouser... And...

508
00:33:18,624 --> 00:33:20,558
Curiouser.

509
00:33:20,559 --> 00:33:23,261
- See?
I knew you were real.

510
00:33:26,899 --> 00:33:28,300
I was real?

511
00:33:28,601 --> 00:33:31,303
Yes.
I knew it wasn't a story.

512
00:33:32,872 --> 00:33:34,666
What wasn't a story?

513
00:33:34,707 --> 00:33:37,909
The fisherman.
The girl in the net.

514
00:33:39,044 --> 00:33:40,412
Ah.

515
00:33:41,113 --> 00:33:43,649
My da told me a story about you.

516
00:33:45,618 --> 00:33:48,113
Your dad is Syracuse?

517
00:33:48,154 --> 00:33:50,702
- Yeah, the fisherman.

518
00:33:50,743 --> 00:33:53,926
So, do you have magic powers?

519
00:33:54,427 --> 00:33:55,460
- Do you?

520
00:33:55,491 --> 00:33:56,992
You know I don't.

521
00:33:57,693 --> 00:33:59,765
Okay, you don't.

522
00:34:00,466 --> 00:34:02,567
Can you make me better?

523
00:34:03,969 --> 00:34:05,304
Better?

524
00:34:05,345 --> 00:34:06,505
- I'm sick.

525
00:34:06,536 --> 00:34:09,574
I've got kidney failure.
Didn't he tell you?

526
00:34:13,413 --> 00:34:16,632
What's your name?
- It's Annie.

527
00:34:16,683 --> 00:34:18,651
Annie.

528
00:34:19,652 --> 00:34:21,900
I'm Ondine.

529
00:34:21,941 --> 00:34:23,955
Ondine.

530
00:34:26,392 --> 00:34:29,488
I'm examining you for webs.

531
00:34:29,529 --> 00:34:32,337
Well, do I disappoint you?

532
00:34:32,398 --> 00:34:34,259
Ondine is French, isn't it?

533
00:34:34,900 --> 00:34:37,562
What's a French selkie doing here?

534
00:34:37,603 --> 00:34:39,538
Who said I was French?

535
00:34:39,579 --> 00:34:42,607
You got lost, did you?

536
00:34:43,576 --> 00:34:47,272
Yes...
I suppose I did get lost.

537
00:34:47,313 --> 00:34:48,774
You cold?

538
00:34:48,815 --> 00:34:49,815
- Suddenly.

539
00:34:49,856 --> 00:34:51,249
Because you're on land now.

540
00:34:51,280 --> 00:34:54,518
Your natural habitat
is in the water, you see.

541
00:34:55,321 --> 00:34:57,258
- You seem to know a lot about me.

542
00:34:57,299 --> 00:34:59,890
Yes. I've been reading...

543
00:35:00,131 --> 00:35:02,161
...Researching.

544
00:35:02,462 --> 00:35:04,122
Want to come inside?

545
00:35:04,163 --> 00:35:07,626
- If I walk across the threshold,
you might put a hex on me.

546
00:35:07,667 --> 00:35:08,933
What's a hex?

547
00:35:08,974 --> 00:35:12,070
 - It's bad news, a hex.

548
00:35:19,111 --> 00:35:22,003
- Maybe underwater feels better.

549
00:35:22,044 --> 00:35:23,742
Better than what?

550
00:35:24,383 --> 00:35:26,345
Some days I'm sick all the time.

551
00:35:26,396 --> 00:35:28,908
Does it feel better underwater?

552
00:35:30,089 --> 00:35:31,890
I'm not sure I know what you mean.

553
00:35:31,931 --> 00:35:33,157
- Oh, come on.

554
00:35:33,198 --> 00:35:34,773
Let's not try and fool each other.

555
00:35:34,804 --> 00:35:36,331
We both know the truth.

556
00:35:36,362 --> 00:35:37,796
And if we're not straightforward,

557
00:35:37,837 --> 00:35:39,297
there's no point in being friends.

558
00:35:39,338 --> 00:35:41,466
Ah.

559
00:35:41,497 --> 00:35:43,905
So we're to be friends, then?

560
00:35:43,946 --> 00:35:47,709
We could be...
If we play our cards right.

561
00:35:47,740 --> 00:35:49,608
So I need you to be specific.

562
00:35:49,649 --> 00:35:53,678
Does it feel better in that
home of yours under the waves?

563
00:35:55,748 --> 00:35:59,150
Well, it definitely feels different.

564
00:35:59,251 --> 00:36:02,153
- And I know you don't talk down there.

565
00:36:02,254 --> 00:36:04,089
You sing.

566
00:36:04,690 --> 00:36:08,126
Yes. Singing travels better underwater.

567
00:36:08,827 --> 00:36:10,796
And what about the cold?

568
00:36:11,397 --> 00:36:13,064
Get used to it.

569
00:36:13,365 --> 00:36:17,101
Oh, of course,
you have your seal coat, don't you?

570
00:36:18,871 --> 00:36:20,151
My seal coat?

571
00:36:20,192 --> 00:36:22,574
Look, there's no point
in beating around the bush.

572
00:36:22,595 --> 00:36:26,210
I do know these things.
I've been studying them.

573
00:36:28,948 --> 00:36:32,884
So, tell me about my seal coat.

574
00:36:32,985 --> 00:36:35,086
- You lose it when you get out of water.

575
00:36:35,287 --> 00:36:37,422
And you can't go back in
until you find it again.

576
00:36:37,473 --> 00:36:40,525
And if you do find it
and bury it on land,

577
00:36:40,576 --> 00:36:44,696
you can stay for seven years,
and you cry seven tears.

578
00:36:44,797 --> 00:36:46,397
But then,
when the crying's done,

579
00:36:46,498 --> 00:36:51,603
your kind of folk can often find
unexpected happiness with a...

580
00:36:51,664 --> 00:36:53,632
What's it called?

581
00:36:53,673 --> 00:36:54,940
Are you lost for words?

582
00:36:54,991 --> 00:36:57,041
A landsman, that's what.

583
00:36:57,092 --> 00:36:59,143
Selkie women often find...
- A landsman.

584
00:36:59,194 --> 00:37:02,013
...unexpected happiness with a landsman.

585
00:37:02,614 --> 00:37:04,415
And that's all I know.

586
00:37:06,519 --> 00:37:10,455
This is my granny's place.
He misses her.

587
00:37:17,129 --> 00:37:18,429
And where do you live?

588
00:37:18,430 --> 00:37:22,501
- With me ma,
and it's not underneath the waves.

589
00:37:22,502 --> 00:37:24,903
She'll be wondering where I am.

590
00:37:28,207 --> 00:37:30,441
See you again.

591
00:37:32,244 --> 00:37:34,345
Your cheek is wet.

592
00:37:34,346 --> 00:37:36,748
Is that one of the seven tears?

593
00:37:36,749 --> 00:37:37,916
Maybe.

594
00:37:37,917 --> 00:37:40,519
You've only six left.

595
00:37:44,957 --> 00:37:46,725
Can I help you there, Circus?

596
00:37:47,006 --> 00:37:49,501
Yeah.
Have you any books on selkies?

597
00:37:49,542 --> 00:37:50,795
Selkies.
We do, actually.

598
00:37:50,836 --> 00:37:52,764
But strangely enough,
they're all out at the moment.

599
00:37:52,799 --> 00:37:53,867
Out?

599
00:37:53,909 --> 00:37:55,567
- If you want to read them,
your daughter has them.

600
00:37:55,598 --> 00:37:58,436
Annie?
- Mmm, Annie. Doing a project, she said.

601
00:37:58,477 --> 00:38:02,601
Yeah. Just trying to help her
get ahead of the game.

602
00:38:02,642 --> 00:38:04,375
- Good man.

603
00:38:07,413 --> 00:38:08,817
Does it do stunts, Annie?

604
00:38:08,848 --> 00:38:10,649
What do you mean,
"stunts"?

605
00:38:10,750 --> 00:38:12,417
Stunts like this.

606
00:38:18,890 --> 00:38:21,492
I don't think
it's a recreational vehicle.

607
00:38:21,613 --> 00:38:22,928
So it's only for spaz?

608
00:38:23,029 --> 00:38:25,109
You don't say "spaz".
You say "special needs".

609
00:38:25,140 --> 00:38:26,297
Don't you, Annie?

610
00:38:26,338 --> 00:38:27,498
Yeah.

611
00:38:27,539 --> 00:38:28,767
- See, you feckin' retard?

612
00:38:28,798 --> 00:38:30,415
Say it.
- Special needs.

613
00:38:30,446 --> 00:38:32,203
Special needs, Annie.

614
00:38:32,204 --> 00:38:33,772
Give us a go?

615
00:38:35,407 --> 00:38:36,741
Does it float?

616
00:38:36,782 --> 00:38:38,710
I don't think it's amphibious.

617
00:38:38,751 --> 00:38:41,813
[ Sighs ]
Special needs, my ass.

618
00:38:50,589 --> 00:38:51,823
Come on, guys.

619
00:38:57,029 --> 00:38:58,831
Is mum up yet?

620
00:38:59,632 --> 00:39:00,933
No.

621
00:39:02,134 --> 00:39:03,301
Was there something up?

622
00:39:03,602 --> 00:39:05,103
Why do you think?

623
00:39:05,194 --> 00:39:06,364
Is it battery trouble?

624
00:39:06,405 --> 00:39:07,872
It got wet.

625
00:39:10,576 --> 00:39:13,111
Come here.
I don't bite.

626
00:39:13,192 --> 00:39:15,714
Come on.
Jesus, you're getting big.

627
00:39:15,785 --> 00:39:17,515
[ Grunts ]

628
00:39:19,184 --> 00:39:21,886
You said you had selkies in Scotland.

629
00:39:21,967 --> 00:39:23,521
Aye.

630
00:39:23,922 --> 00:39:26,891
We invented selkies in the Outer Hebrides.

631
00:39:26,992 --> 00:39:28,159
[ Hair Dryer Blowing ]

632
00:39:28,460 --> 00:39:29,627
You mean you made them up?

633
00:39:29,968 --> 00:39:32,564
No.
No, they're a Scottish thing.

634
00:39:34,934 --> 00:39:36,502
[ Hair Dryer Turns Off ]

635
00:39:37,903 --> 00:39:39,738
[ Wheelchair Beeps ]

636
00:39:41,941 --> 00:39:43,708
There you go.

637
00:39:48,714 --> 00:39:51,182
She doesn't speak like you.

638
00:39:51,383 --> 00:39:53,001
Who?

639
00:39:58,624 --> 00:40:02,360
Oh, we've got secrets,
have we, little girl?

640
00:40:03,996 --> 00:40:05,864
Well, you could say thanks.

641
00:40:05,895 --> 00:40:07,098
Thanks.

642
00:40:07,299 --> 00:40:08,900
[ Chuckles ]

643
00:40:08,961 --> 00:40:10,635
You're welcome.

644
00:40:51,911 --> 00:40:54,278
Do you want to come again?

645
00:40:54,279 --> 00:40:55,513
- Fishing?

646
00:40:55,514 --> 00:40:57,849
Only if you want, like.

647
00:40:58,350 --> 00:41:00,585
You promise I'll see nobody but you?

648
00:41:00,686 --> 00:41:03,021
I promise you'll see nobody but me.

649
00:41:04,957 --> 00:41:06,891
You're swimming in my dress?

650
00:41:09,127 --> 00:41:12,697
It was a gift...
From a fisherman.

651
00:41:12,898 --> 00:41:15,166
[ Chuckles ]

652
00:41:36,021 --> 00:41:38,222
Ondine:
Can I help?

653
00:41:38,423 --> 00:41:40,558
You can man the tiller.

654
00:41:45,698 --> 00:41:49,400
Right.
Straight out to sea.

655
00:41:54,707 --> 00:41:55,773
[ Gasps ]

656
00:41:55,774 --> 00:41:58,075
Keep her steady, would you? 

657
00:41:58,376 --> 00:42:00,545
Fisheries board.

658
00:42:14,727 --> 00:42:18,830
You can't really guide a boat
with your foot.

659
00:42:20,532 --> 00:42:22,033
I'm not doing well?

660
00:42:22,084 --> 00:42:24,035
No, I never said that.

661
00:42:27,606 --> 00:42:30,875
[ ♫ Singing Indistinctly ♫ ]

662
00:42:47,760 --> 00:42:48,930
[ Fishing Reel Clicking ]

663
00:42:48,991 --> 00:42:50,828
Oh, shit.

664
00:43:16,989 --> 00:43:19,057
Would you look at that!

665
00:43:21,093 --> 00:43:23,494
My God.
- What?

666
00:43:24,095 --> 00:43:26,303
That's weird.
Salmon.

667
00:43:26,364 --> 00:43:27,705
Weird?

668
00:43:27,766 --> 00:43:30,267
You don't get salmon trawling.

669
00:43:30,468 --> 00:43:31,509
- Trawling.

670
00:43:31,570 --> 00:43:34,272
Only with a gill net.

671
00:43:34,673 --> 00:43:36,640
- Curiouser and curiouser.

672
00:43:36,681 --> 00:43:38,803
Where did you hear that?

673
00:43:38,844 --> 00:43:40,912
Alice said it.
- To the white rabbit.

674
00:43:40,993 --> 00:43:42,246
Annie says it, too.

675
00:43:42,287 --> 00:43:44,381
Annie?
- My daughter.

676
00:43:49,154 --> 00:43:50,555
Jesus Christ.

677
00:44:12,010 --> 00:44:14,398
Ah... Fuck!
- What?

678
00:44:15,479 --> 00:44:16,147
They're going to come on board.

679
00:44:23,655 --> 00:44:25,056
Lads.

680
00:44:27,025 --> 00:44:28,628
Jesus.

681
00:44:30,929 --> 00:44:33,498
See you caught salmon.
- I did.

682
00:44:33,899 --> 00:44:35,833
How did you catch them?

683
00:44:36,034 --> 00:44:38,803
Trawling.
- And you expect us to believe that?

684
00:44:39,004 --> 00:44:40,537
No, but it's true.

685
00:44:40,578 --> 00:44:43,374
Show us your gill nets.
- In the hold.

686
00:44:50,816 --> 00:44:52,817
That's not wet.
- I know.

687
00:44:52,868 --> 00:44:53,918
So, how'd you dry it?

688
00:44:53,989 --> 00:44:56,320
I didn't.
Told you, I didn't use it.

689
00:45:03,595 --> 00:45:05,529
There's a girl here, Circus.
- Where?

690
00:45:05,730 --> 00:45:07,198
In your net.

691
00:45:07,999 --> 00:45:09,233
[ Clears Throat ]

692
00:45:09,334 --> 00:45:10,998
Is that illegal?

693
00:45:11,269 --> 00:45:13,938
No, but... It's unusual.

694
00:45:14,339 --> 00:45:16,144
And you can see her?

695
00:45:16,175 --> 00:45:17,574
- She's right here in front of me.

696
00:45:17,875 --> 00:45:19,343
Ask her how I caught the salmon.

697
00:45:19,994 --> 00:45:21,313
How'd he catch them?

698
00:45:23,114 --> 00:45:24,702
Trawling.

699
00:45:24,783 --> 00:45:27,618
- And you want us
to believe in fairy tales?

700
00:45:27,819 --> 00:45:28,986
Yes.

701
00:45:30,722 --> 00:45:33,157
Huh?
What did she say?

702
00:45:33,198 --> 00:45:34,922
She said yes.

703
00:45:34,993 --> 00:45:36,928
Well, then,
you'd better believe her.

704
00:45:36,979 --> 00:45:39,663
Right.
Close it up, lads.

705
00:46:01,220 --> 00:46:03,321
[ Laughs ]

706
00:46:04,990 --> 00:46:07,408
So, they saw you.

707
00:46:07,459 --> 00:46:09,307
Is that all right?

708
00:46:09,348 --> 00:46:10,527
No.

709
00:46:10,578 --> 00:46:13,464
- It's a relief in a way.
Means you're not in my mind.

710
00:46:13,495 --> 00:46:15,933
- Means they'll talk.
'Course they will.

711
00:46:17,935 --> 00:46:19,603
What will they say?

712
00:46:19,774 --> 00:46:22,303
- Ah, take your pick.

713
00:46:22,374 --> 00:46:26,543
Circus, clowns,
salmon, a girl. 

714
00:46:27,812 --> 00:46:30,381
I'm going to the harbor.
Do you want me to drop you off?

715
00:46:34,486 --> 00:46:36,754
It's done, isn't it?

716
00:46:36,895 --> 00:46:38,702
What's done?

717
00:46:38,743 --> 00:46:40,691
I've been seen.

718
00:46:56,275 --> 00:46:59,247
Here, take a look at the girl
coming in on that boat.

719
00:46:59,278 --> 00:47:01,012
She's not bad, is she?

720
00:47:01,073 --> 00:47:03,314
It is a small town.

721
00:47:03,415 --> 00:47:05,316
Everyone stares.

722
00:47:06,919 --> 00:47:09,153
You can say that again.

723
00:47:09,354 --> 00:47:11,389
What's wrong with being seen?

724
00:47:13,292 --> 00:47:14,658
Nothing...

725
00:47:14,689 --> 00:47:17,328
when you look good.

726
00:47:17,429 --> 00:47:19,797
You look mighty.

727
00:47:22,067 --> 00:47:23,704
I'm going to have to
declare these, Circus.

728
00:47:23,735 --> 00:47:25,403
They've already seen them.
- Who?

729
00:47:25,454 --> 00:47:26,804
The fisheries.

730
00:47:29,141 --> 00:47:30,674
They're fine, believe me.

731
00:47:34,846 --> 00:47:36,613
Thanks, Mary.

732
00:47:41,386 --> 00:47:43,321
Can I buy you a present?

733
00:47:44,122 --> 00:47:45,622
Clothes.

734
00:47:45,663 --> 00:47:47,925
But can I choose this time?
- You don't like the dress?

735
00:47:47,966 --> 00:47:52,229
No, I like it, just...
Underwear could be better.

736
00:47:52,280 --> 00:47:54,165
Didn't fit?

737
00:47:54,566 --> 00:47:56,808
Tight around the edges.

738
00:47:57,769 --> 00:47:59,370
You have edges?

739
00:47:59,871 --> 00:48:01,973
[ Wheelchair Beeps ]

740
00:48:04,542 --> 00:48:07,244
I knew it wasn't a story.
- What wasn't a story?

741
00:48:07,285 --> 00:48:09,246
You're such a shite storyteller anyway.

742
00:48:09,287 --> 00:48:11,148
I knew it had to be true.

743
00:48:11,199 --> 00:48:14,518
Ondine, this is my daughter, Annie.

744
00:48:14,559 --> 00:48:16,354
We've met before.

745
00:48:16,395 --> 00:48:17,721
Yes, we have.

746
00:48:17,762 --> 00:48:19,850
What are we doing?

747
00:48:19,891 --> 00:48:22,526
Buying clothes.
- Okay.

748
00:48:26,764 --> 00:48:31,135
This town is what you'd call
sartorially challenged.

749
00:48:31,436 --> 00:48:33,771
What does that mean?

750
00:48:33,972 --> 00:48:36,773
A supermodel's nightmare.

751
00:48:39,577 --> 00:48:41,078
[ Annie whistles ]

752
00:48:44,616 --> 00:48:47,651
Do selkies do lingerie?

753
00:48:47,852 --> 00:48:49,587
Why not?

754
00:48:49,908 --> 00:48:53,724
They wear seaweed knickers
 and a scallopy bra.

755
00:48:53,825 --> 00:48:55,559
But that's underwater.

756
00:48:55,760 --> 00:48:57,930
Won't do here.

757
00:48:59,131 --> 00:49:01,765
I'm not suggesting she buy
them all, da.

758
00:49:01,866 --> 00:49:03,834
Just a selection.

759
00:49:07,805 --> 00:49:12,336
That's where I found her --
Roan Carraig.

760
00:49:12,377 --> 00:49:14,472
- You know what it means?

761
00:49:14,513 --> 00:49:16,247
Seal rock.

762
00:49:16,348 --> 00:49:20,017
It's a kind of sanctuary
for her kind.

763
00:49:20,218 --> 00:49:21,852
Her kind?

764
00:49:21,893 --> 00:49:24,955
Yeah.
The well-dressed kind.

765
00:49:28,826 --> 00:49:30,894
What do you think?

766
00:49:32,830 --> 00:49:34,765
Or should we say
what do 'they' think?

767
00:50:04,629 --> 00:50:06,797
You cleaned the place.

768
00:50:08,766 --> 00:50:10,801
Like Snow White.

769
00:50:13,838 --> 00:50:15,206
Is that all right?

770
00:50:15,407 --> 00:50:17,441
But I'm not a dwarf, you know.

771
00:50:17,492 --> 00:50:20,478
I'm little, but I'm not a dwarf.

772
00:50:20,979 --> 00:50:22,613
Who is Snow White?

773
00:50:22,674 --> 00:50:25,983
Doesn't matter.
She didn't swim.

774
00:50:29,254 --> 00:50:31,054
Can you swim, Annie?

775
00:50:31,155 --> 00:50:34,658
No. There's no pool in the town,
and I've never had lessons.

776
00:50:35,259 --> 00:50:37,861
I think it could relax you a lot.

777
00:50:39,098 --> 00:50:41,865
Unless you have a fear of water.

778
00:50:41,966 --> 00:50:46,203
I wouldn't have a fear of water
with a water creature around me.

779
00:50:51,109 --> 00:50:53,877
Okay, then.
Come on.

780
00:50:56,481 --> 00:50:58,149
What'll I wear?

781
00:50:59,984 --> 00:51:01,885
Underwear.

782
00:51:10,962 --> 00:51:12,929
She's gone already.

783
00:51:13,670 --> 00:51:14,952
Where?

784
00:51:15,033 --> 00:51:17,135
The caravan at Poulin.

785
00:51:17,536 --> 00:51:20,704
Is that where she sleeps,
your water baby?

786
00:51:31,082 --> 00:51:34,485
Thought I might
take her out for the day.

787
00:51:34,586 --> 00:51:36,119
The regatta starts at 3:00.

788
00:51:36,160 --> 00:51:38,579
Oh, the three of you.

789
00:51:38,590 --> 00:51:41,091
Go diving for pearls?

790
00:51:42,927 --> 00:51:44,928
Something like that.

791
00:51:47,632 --> 00:51:50,133
What kind of stories are you spinning?

792
00:51:50,434 --> 00:51:52,269
[ Sighs ]

793
00:51:54,838 --> 00:51:56,541
Just relax.

794
00:51:57,542 --> 00:51:59,076
Okay.

795
00:51:59,477 --> 00:52:02,346
Lie down now.
I'll hold you.

796
00:52:04,882 --> 00:52:06,400
You see?

797
00:52:06,651 --> 00:52:09,106
You see?
You're a sea creature.

798
00:52:09,157 --> 00:52:10,781
You think?
- I know.

799
00:52:10,822 --> 00:52:12,623
[ Both Laugh ]

800
00:52:12,924 --> 00:52:15,459
Relax.
Relax.

801
00:52:19,297 --> 00:52:22,399
Okay. Let's go on the raft, okay?

802
00:52:31,643 --> 00:52:33,210
[ Panting ]

803
00:52:33,311 --> 00:52:34,780
[ Inhales Deeply ]

804
00:52:46,858 --> 00:52:47,891
What's that?

805
00:52:47,932 --> 00:52:49,493
Just something I found.

806
00:52:49,634 --> 00:52:51,328
You found your seal coat.

807
00:52:51,529 --> 00:52:52,529
Maybe.

808
00:52:52,580 --> 00:52:54,765
Are you going to bury it?

809
00:52:54,866 --> 00:52:56,368
Would you like me to bury it?

810
00:52:56,468 --> 00:52:59,403
Yes, because it means
you'll be here for seven years.

811
00:52:59,454 --> 00:53:01,138
Would you like that?

812
00:53:01,339 --> 00:53:03,140
I would like that a lot.

813
00:53:03,741 --> 00:53:05,876
We better bury it then, do you think?

814
